unts the history of the most sweeping attempt to sort and categorize the nation's enormous population: the 1954 Ethnic Classification project (minzu shibie). Thomas S. Mullaney draws on recently declassified material and extensive oral histories to describe how the communist government, in power less than a decade, launched this process in ethnically diverse Yunnan. Mullaney shows how the government drew on Republican-era scholarship for conceptual and methodological inspiration as it developed a strategy for identifying minzu and how non-Party-member Chinese ethnologists produced a "scientific" survey that would become the basis for a policy on nationalities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnicityzChina. 0aEthnologyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinoritiesxGovernment policyzChina. 0aMinoritieszChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a1954 ethnic classification project.  aasia.  achinese government.  acommunist government.  acontroversial.  acultural histories.  adistinct languages.  adiversity.  aethnic classification.  aethnic communities.  aethnic histories.  aethnic nationalities.  aethnic representation.  aethnographers.  aglobal politics.  aminzu shibie.  aminzu.  amodern china.  amodern history.  amulticulturalism.  anationalism.  anon party chinese ethnologists.  anonfiction.  aoral histories.  apolicy on nationalities.  ayunnan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026278240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094763440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805209